Sea Floor Topography

  • Oceans cover ~71% of Earthâs surface and have an average depth of nearly 4,000 metres.
  • The sea floor is shaped by plate tectonics and features a wide range of topographic elements.
  • It is largely hidden beneath deep waters, making study difficult, but bathymetric surveys have greatly advanced our understanding.

Major Sea Floor Features

The generalised topography of the Pacific Ocean sea floor between Japan and British Columbia. The vertical exaggeration is approximately 200 times. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Continental Shelves
  • Continental Slopes
  • Abyssal Plains
  • Mid-Ocean Ridges
  • Seamounts
  • Trenches

Continental Shelves

  • Shallow, submerged edges of continents, usually <200 m deep.
  • Extend for tens to hundreds of kilometers offshore.
  • Rich in marine lifeâlocated within the photic zone.
  • Examples: Nova Scotiaâs shelf is wide; British Columbiaâs is narrow due to tectonic activity.

Continental Slopes

  • Mark the transition from continental crust to oceanic crust.
  • Slopes descend steeply from shelf edge to abyssal plainâdepths increase from ~200 m to several thousand meters.

Abyssal Plains

  • Extremely flat and deep ocean floors (typically 4,000â6,000 m deep).
  • Covered with thick layers of fine sediments.
  • Represent some of the flattest surfaces on Earth.

Mid-Ocean Ridges

  • Underwater mountain chains formed at divergent plate boundaries.
  • Created by seafloor spreading (e.g., Mid-Atlantic Ridge).
  • Often shallower than surrounding seafloor (sometimes <3,000 m).

Seamounts

  • Isolated volcanic peaks rising from the ocean floor, not breaking the surface.
  • Often formed by hotspot volcanism or near plate boundaries.

Trenches

  • Deep, narrow depressions at subduction zones.
  • Among the deepest places on Earth (e.g., Mariana Trench ~11,000 m deep).
  • Formed where one tectonic plate is subducted beneath another.

Subduction Zones and Trench Formation

The generalised topography of the Pacific Ocean floor in the area of the Marianas Trench, near Guam. The dashed grey line represents the subduction of the Pacific Plate (to the right) beneath the Philippine Plate (to the left). Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Trenches form where oceanic crust is forced beneath another plate.
  • Sediment fill affects trench visibilityâe.g., no visible trench off British Columbia due to Fraser River sediment.
  • Marianas Trench: the deepest known ocean trench (11,000 m).
  • Other notable trenches: Japan, Peru-Chile, and Puerto Rico Trenches.

Bathymetric Profiles and Vertical Exaggeration

  • Bathymetric profiles often exaggerate vertical scale to highlight features.
  • Example: Vertical exaggeration of 200x shows steep slopes and tall ridges that appear more pronounced than they are.
  • In reality, abyssal plains are flatter than most land surfaces.

The Geology of the Oceanic Crust

Composition and Structure of Oceanic Crust

Schematic representation of the lithologic layers of typical oceanic crust (Ophiolite). Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Layer Approximate Depth Composition
Ocean floor sediments 0 â 0.5 km Limestone, mudstone, chert, turbidites
Volcanic layer 0.5 â 1.0 km Pillow basalts, breccias, basaltic flows
Sheeted dykes 1.0 â 2.0 km Vertical conduits feeding the lavas
Gabbro bodies 2.0 â 5.0 km Coarse-grained mafic intrusive rock

Layered peridotite 6.0 â 6.5 km Ultramafic rocks from the lower crust

Formation Process at Mid-Ocean Ridges

  • Oceanic crust forms at divergent plate boundariesâspecifically, at mid-ocean ridges.
  • Decompression melting of rising hot mantle rock generates mafic magma.
  • The magma forms:
    • Pillow basalts at the surface
    • Sheeted dykes that feed the lava
    • Gabbros and ultramafic rocks in deeper layers
  • Over time, these layers are buried under marine sediments.

Age of Oceanic Crust and Magnetic Anomalies

Magnetics Polarity of the seafloor. Source: https://divediscover.whoi.edu

  • Oceanic crust is geologically young:
    • Most is less than 100 million years old
    • The oldest known oceanic crust is ~280 Ma
  • Magnetic stripes on the seafloor record Earthâs magnetic reversals:
    • Symmetrical patterns on either side of ridges help determine crust age
    • Faster spreading ridges show wider age bands (e.g., East Pacific Rise)
    • Slower ridges show narrower bands (e.g., Mid-Atlantic Ridge)

Seamounts and Hotspot Volcanism

  • Seamounts are underwater volcanoes, many of which do not reach the ocean surface.
  • Formed by:
    • Hotspots: Stationary plumes of magma (e.g., Hawaii, Galapagos)
      • Older volcanoes move away from the hotspot and subside
      • Example: HawaiianâEmperor Chain
    • Subduction zones: Create volcanic arcs like the Aleutians and Lesser Antilles
  • Not all seamount chains show a clear age progression (e.g., Line Islands formed by rifting)

Formation of Reefs and Atolls

The formation of a fringing reef, a barrier reef, and an atoll around a subsiding tropical volcanic island. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Coral reefs often form around tropical volcanic islands:
    • Fringing reef develops around an active island
    • Barrier reef forms as the island subsides and a lagoon develops
    • Atoll results when the volcanic island is fully submerged, but the reef remains
  • These features are controlled by:
    • Sea-level rise (e.g., post-glacial)
    • Volcanic subsidence
  • If subsidence is slow, the reef can keep up with sea level and remain near the surface

Sea-Floor Sediments

Types of Sea-Floor Sediment

  • Terrigenous Sediment
  • Pelagic Carbonate Sediment
  • Pelagic Silica Sediment
  • Volcanic Material
  • Iron-Manganese Nodules

Terrigenous Sediment

  • Origin: Weathering and erosion of continental rocks
  • Transported by: Rivers, glaciers, wind, ocean currents
  • Composition: Quartz, feldspar, clay minerals, iron oxides, organic matter
  • Location: Near continental margins, in inland seas and large lakes
  • Grain size: Coarse nearshore (sand, silt); clay-sized particles transported further offshore

Pelagic Carbonate Sediment

  • Origin: Microscopic marine organisms (e.g., foraminifera) that build shells of calcite
  • Depositional zones: Shallow to mid-depth ocean regions with high biological productivity
  • Form: Carbonate ooze, which lithifies over time into limestone
  • Limit: Dissolves below the carbonate compensation depth (CCD)

Pelagic Silica Sediment

  • Origin: Silica-secreting marine organisms (e.g., diatoms, radiolaria)
  • Depositional zones: Equatorial Pacific, southern ocean regions, and beneath high productivity zones
  • Form: Siliceous ooze, lithifies into chert

Volcanic Material

  • Origin: Submarine and terrestrial eruptions
  • Types: Volcanic ash, pyroclastic fragments, lava
  • Location: Near volcanic arcs and oceanic hotspots

Iron-Manganese Nodules

  • Origin: Direct chemical precipitation from seawater
  • Composition: Concentric layers of manganese and iron oxides
  • Location: Deep ocean basins, away from rapid sediment accumulation
  • Notes: Nodules grow very slowly over millions of years

Sediment Distribution Patterns

The distribution of sediment types on the sea floor. Within each coloured area, the type of material shown is what dominates, although other materials are also likely to be present. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Near continents: Coarse terrigenous sediments dominate
  • Open oceans: Fine-grained clay, carbonate ooze, and siliceous ooze predominate
  • Equatorial and mid-latitude regions: High carbonate productivity (carbonate oozes)
  • Polar and equatorial upwelling zones: High silica productivity (siliceous oozes)
  • Deep basins (>4000 m): Dominated by clay and silica, as carbonate dissolves below the CCD

Carbonate Compensation Depth (CCD)

  • Definition: The depth at which the rate of carbonate dissolution equals its supply
  • Typical depth: Around 4,000 metres, but varies with temperature and pressure
  • Above CCD: Carbonate accumulates
  • Below CCD: Carbonate dissolves; no carbonate ooze forms
  • Result: Carbonate sediments are restricted to shallower parts of ocean basins (e.g., mid-ocean ridges, seamount tops)

Methane Hydrates

Left: Methane hydrate within muddy sea-floor sediment from an area offshore from Oregon. Right: Methane hydrate on fire. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

What Are Methane Hydrates?

  • Methane hydrate, also called methane clathrate, is a crystalline solid in which methane (CHâ) gas molecules are trapped within cages of water molecules, forming a structure similar to ice. It is stable under low temperature and moderate to high pressure conditions, typically found in:
    • Marine sediments on continental slopes (500â1,000 m depth)
    • Permafrost regions in the Arctic
  • Methane hydrate looks like ice but releases flammable methane gas when warmed or depressurized.

Formation

  • Produced by anaerobic decomposition of organic matter in sediments
  • Methane (CHâ) combines with water at low temperatures and moderate pressures to form methane hydrate

Location

  • Found on continental slopes at depths of 500 to 1,000 m
  • Stable under conditions of low temperature (~4Â°C) and high pressure

Climate Implications

  • Represents a massive reservoir of fossil carbon
  • Potential as an energy resource
  • Concern: Methane is a potent greenhouse gas
    • Release could exacerbate climate change
    • Past methane releases have been linked to abrupt paleoclimate events

Ocean Water

Composition and Salinity of Seawater

Seawater is salty because it contains dissolved ions derived from weathering of continental rocks and hydrothermal processes at mid-ocean ridges.

Major Dissolved Ions in Seawater (by weight)

The proportions (by weight) of the major dissolved elements in ocean water. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Ion Source
Chloride (Clâ») Weathering of rocks, volcanic gases
Sodium (Naâº) Weathering of feldspars and other silicates
Sulfate (SOâÂ²â») Volcanic gases, oxidation of sulfides
Magnesium (MgÂ²âº) Crustal weathering
Calcium (CaÂ²âº) Used biologically (e.g., for carbonate shells)
Potassium (Kâº) Weathering of feldspars and micas
  • The average salinity of ocean water is 35 g/L, or 3.5%.
  • Most of the salt is sodium chloride (NaCl), but seawater also contains magnesium, sulfate, calcium, and trace elements.

Salinity Variation and Causes

  • Salinity is not uniform and varies with:
    • Evaporation (increases salinity)
    • River inflow / precipitation (decreases salinity)
    • Sea ice formation (increases salinity of surrounding water)
    • Sea ice melting (lowers salinity)

Salinity Patterns:

  • Lowest salinity: Arctic Ocean and near river mouths (e.g., Amazon, Ganges)
  • Highest salinity: Semi-enclosed seas in hot dry climates (e.g., Red Sea, Mediterranean Sea)

Despite large river inputs into the Mediterranean, evaporation exceeds inflow, so Atlantic water flows into the Mediterranean through the Strait of Gibraltar.

Ocean temperatures vary with latitude and depth.

  • Warmest waters are found in the tropics, coldest at the poles
  • Currents like the Gulf Stream redistribute heat from equator to higher latitudes

Ocean Currents

Ocean currents are critical for heat redistribution and climate regulation.

Surface Currents

  • Driven by wind and influenced by Earthâs rotation (Coriolis effect):
    • Currents deflect clockwise in the Northern Hemisphere
    • Counterclockwise in the Southern Hemisphere
  • These large-scale current systems are called gyres.

Examples:

  • Gulf Stream: Warm current flowing from the tropics to the North Atlantic
  • California Current: Cold current flowing south along the U.S. west coast
  • Labrador Current: Cold current bringing icebergs past Newfoundland

Deep-Ocean Circulation (Thermohaline Circulation)

A depiction of the vertical movement of water along a north-south cross-section through the Atlantic basin. Source: Steven, E. (2015)

  • Driven by differences in water density, which depends on temperature and salinity
  • Referred to as the Global Ocean Conveyor Belt

Key Components:

  • North Atlantic Deep Water (NADW): Forms as salty Gulf Stream water cools and sinks in the North Atlantic
  • Antarctic Bottom Water (AABW): Very cold, dense water formed around Antarctica that sinks and flows northward beneath NADW

Importance of Ocean Circulation to Global Climate

  • Transports heat from equator to poles
  • Distributes nutrients and gases through the ocean
  • Regulates regional climates:
    • Western Europe is warmer than eastern Canada at similar latitudes due to the Gulf Stream
  • Disruptions to thermohaline circulation can cause rapid climate shifts, as evidenced during the Pleistocene glaciations
